<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-03-22T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-03-22T22:00:00-05:00" n="73" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d73">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/774: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Castle</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-03-23T12:00:00+09:00">March 23,
                                1930—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received March 23—4:33
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>55. Your 55, March 21, 5 p.m.<note n="91a" xml:id="d73fn91a">See footnote
                                89, <ref target="#pg_71">p. 71</ref>.</note> Repeat to London.<note n="92" xml:id="d73fn92">Transmitted to the American delegation as
                                Department’s telegram No. 248.</note></p>
                        <p>Wakatsuki gave out a statement that this is not an American proposal but
                            an agreement which was reached by three delegations. His statement was
                            published in all the Japanese newspapers yesterday morning.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>